Text.Value: It's sparse thanks for what you've done for us but, gods and goblins willing, I won't need it again.

EditorData.NodeContext: Grateful

Text.Value: Once the druids complete their ritual, we'll be sharing the road with goblins once again.

EditorData.NodeContext: Frustrated but resigned

Text.Value: Halsin's alive - he's being held captive by goblins.
But they're ill-disciplined. It's unusual for them to organise so cleverly.
There have been several attacks by different monsters. The druids blame us 'outsiders' for drawing them here. Nobody's welcome anymore.

EditorData.NodeContext: Explaning a serious situation - the mention of 'outsiders' is bitter - his people always get blamed for everything

Text.Value: What little we have, we'll scrape together. It isn't coin we need - it's time.

EditorData.NodeContext: Accepting your request for payment for helping him

Text.Value: Better to leave on your own terms before it comes to that. I'll help.
Truly? Ilmater's ashes, I never thought she would actually see reason. Too late for poor Arabella.

EditorData.NodeContext: Genuinely surprised, please - but last sentence tinged with bitterness and sadness - it won't bring the dead back, so he has to look forward

Text.Value: We're refugees from Elturel - we took shelter here after gnolls and goblins attacked us on the road.
I know you'll do the right thing.
We got out alive. That's what matters. And you did too, by the looks of things.
The High Overseer - our grand protector - signed a pact with devils. It dragged Elturel straight to Hell.
But we can't get there with those beasts blocking our path.
Let's not forget why we're here. No point in wasting precious time on a lost cause.
Right. Best not to stop here.

EditorData.NodeContext: Matter-of-fact. Playuer isn't being particularly friendly, so neither is zevlor

Text.Value: You'll find him in the caves. But we won't stay here much longer.
That's exactly what I'm suggesting.
Right. I'd offer you supplies and sustenance by way of thanks, but I'm afraid there's little to spare.

EditorData.NodeContext: Friendly but harried.

Text.Value: Have you spoken to Kagha?

EditorData.NodeContext: Waiting for news
EditorData.logicalname: AGREED TO SPEAK TO KAGHA, DRUID COURT NOT DONE

Text.Value: By the Triad, there is only one correct answer. Refuse him, and we sentence these people to die.
Lucky for you, you seem to have spooked Aradin and his trash into leaving.
If the druids are this far gone, then it's not just goblins we have to fear.

EditorData.NodeContext: Worried, still in shock

Text.Value: I'm told the druids have stopped their damn chanting. What happened?

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Tells that once to each player, as long as a player doesn't tell him explicitely about Kagha
EditorData.logicalname: RitualStopped->need to tell Zev->HasMet on QN

Text.Value: I figured I was due a makeover. What do you think?
To see Kagha pay? Everything. You'll get your coin.

EditorData.NodeContext: No hesitation

Text.Value: I'm looking for the one called 'Zorru'.
I'm looking for a man named Zorru.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: Blocked if the player killed Zorru before talking to Zevlor because I don't see how Zorru could die otherwise

Text.Value: Leaving's the grove is the best option. I can help.
I'm not your messenger.
I want to discuss something else.
Just keep your fists to yourself, yes?

EditorData.NodeContext: Wry but hint of warning - we started our relationship with this man by punching him in the face. He's cautiously welcoming us.

Text.Value: There's the First Druid Halsin. This is his grove. Was, I should say.

EditorData.NodeContext: Factual explanation

Text.Value: Perhaps you could persuade her. For more time to prepare, if nothing else.

EditorData.NodeContext: Being realistic about his chances of concession, not asking too much

Text.Value: No, you won't - I'm here to make sure you leave.
You'll find the druids at the heart of the grove. Please - make them see sense, before more lives are lost.
Raise your hand to one of us again, however, and every tiefling in this encampment will fall on you like a tide.
Try his apprentice, Nettie. You'll find her in the druids' circle.

EditorData.InternalNodeContext: This node doesn't set LearnedLostHalsin in GLO_Tadpole to make the player focus on Nettie

Text.Value: I'll ensure my people make the most of it. It pains me that I have nothing to give you in thanks.

EditorData.NodeContext: Suddenly industrious, looking forward - regretful he hasn't anything to give us

Text.Value: I have no quarrel with druids.
We've our problems, granted, but there might be some merit in shutting down a local conflict, no?

Synopsis:
In these dialogues, Zevlor reflects on what's happened (an attack of goblins at the gate, which the player helped with) and his mistrust of and bitterness towards the druids who are reluctantly hosting his people. He is exasperated, furious, but also eager to meet anyone who could help. 
In the same dialogue, we can also uncover that he is in fact a traitor, concerned only with getting these people through the goblins so he can trade them for his own safety later. In truth he is resentful and contemptuous of them, viewing them as weak.
